WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.542 --> 00:00:03.336
The success of our VQE algorithm heavily

2
00:00:03.336 --> 00:00:06.464
depends on the state and circuit
we choose to begin with.

3
00:00:06.881 --> 00:00:10.802
I'm Victoria Lipinska and in this video
we'll explore the options

4
00:00:10.802 --> 00:00:11.845
we have in designing them.

5
00:00:11.845 --> 00:00:15.473
Let's take a closer
look at all the elements

6
00:00:15.473 --> 00:00:18.643
we have in every run of the quantum
part of the VQE.

7
00:00:19.394 --> 00:00:23.189
We begin with the reference state,
sometimes called initial state.

8
00:00:23.481 --> 00:00:27.193
We run the reference state
through a parameterized circuit called

9
00:00:27.235 --> 00:00:30.697
a variational form
with an initial choice of parameters,

10
00:00:31.281 --> 00:00:34.743
and we measure the state
in the basis of the Hamiltonian

11
00:00:34.993 --> 00:00:40.165
after running it through the circuit
to obtain the expectation value. Now

12
00:00:40.165 --> 00:00:44.210
we'll walk through each of these elements,
starting with the reference state.

13
00:00:44.836 --> 00:00:48.298
A typical choice for the reference
state is the zero state.

14
00:00:48.465 --> 00:00:52.969
That is the state in which a quantum
computer is already initialized.

15
00:00:52.969 --> 00:00:55.346
For quantum chemistry problems,

16
00:00:55.346 --> 00:00:59.017
one can also use the so-called
Hartree-Fock State,

17
00:00:59.017 --> 00:01:01.770
which is the result of a Hartree-Fock
method.

18
00:01:02.437 --> 00:01:06.607
In a nutshell, Hartree-Fock
theory gives a simple way to construct

19
00:01:06.608 --> 00:01:10.987
the reference state by approximating
the ground state of a quantum system.

20
00:01:11.654 --> 00:01:14.532
It finds a rotation
within the space of states

21
00:01:14.783 --> 00:01:16.993
that minimizes the ground state energy.

22
00:01:17.535 --> 00:01:22.415
Finally, the reference state
can also be very problem specific,

23
00:01:22.624 --> 00:01:25.543
and you may want to choose
a custom state.

24
00:01:25.543 --> 00:01:30.172
In the case when you know what properties
your system has, for example, symmetries

25
00:01:30.173 --> 00:01:34.177
or a specific number of electrons
in the state, you can use that

26
00:01:34.427 --> 00:01:38.515
to have better convergence of the VQE
algorithm.

27
00:01:38.515 --> 00:01:42.310
Choosing a good reference
state is important for convergence

28
00:01:42.644 --> 00:01:45.271
reference states that are close to
the ground state

29
00:01:45.438 --> 00:01:48.733
can make the problem converge
much easier and faster.

30
00:01:49.275 --> 00:01:53.530
Similarly important
is the choice of initial parameter values

31
00:01:53.738 --> 00:01:56.407
that we feed into the variational form.

32
00:01:57.075 --> 00:02:00.703
Therefore, depending on the reference
state and initial parameters,

33
00:02:00.912 --> 00:02:04.874
we may converge quickly, slowly
or not converge at all.

34
00:02:05.500 --> 00:02:08.919
Let's look at this plot
and for visualization purposes,

35
00:02:08.919 --> 00:02:13.925
let's imagine that our space of parameters
has only one parameter.

36
00:02:14.634 --> 00:02:18.304
A very good reference state
can allow you to start very close

37
00:02:18.304 --> 00:02:22.058
to the final ground state
and then convergence will be fast.

38
00:02:22.725 --> 00:02:26.688
On the other hand, if you start very far
from the ground state here,

39
00:02:26.688 --> 00:02:30.733
reference state
a, you will have to cross a high energy

40
00:02:30.733 --> 00:02:35.530
barrier leading to a very slow convergence
or no convergence at all.

41
00:02:35.947 --> 00:02:39.576
We will discuss this in more depth
in the classical optimization module

42
00:02:39.576 --> 00:02:40.952
in this course.

43
00:02:41.119 --> 00:02:45.582
Let's now look at the parameter circuit
that acts on the reference state, a.k.a.

44
00:02:45.748 --> 00:02:47.667
the variational form.

45
00:02:47.667 --> 00:02:50.962
When this circuit, the know,
the U of theta acts on the reference

46
00:02:50.962 --> 00:02:54.048
state,
it produces what we call a trial state

47
00:02:54.215 --> 00:02:57.718
psi of theta or sometimes ansatz.

48
00:02:57.719 --> 00:03:02.056
It is this ansatz state that is
then measured in an appropriate basis

49
00:03:02.307 --> 00:03:05.310
to obtain expectation
value for the energy.

50
00:03:05.935 --> 00:03:08.396
The variational forms
that we're discussing here

51
00:03:08.396 --> 00:03:10.481
are motivated by chemistry.

52
00:03:10.899 --> 00:03:13.776
However, keep in mind
that there are also those inspired

53
00:03:13.776 --> 00:03:17.030
by quantum machine learning
and other near-term

54
00:03:17.071 --> 00:03:20.617
algorithms like quantum
approximate optimization algorithms.

55
00:03:21.492 --> 00:03:24.787
Let's discuss
some common choices for a chemistry ansatz.

56
00:03:25.455 --> 00:03:27.916
Unitary coupled cluster or UCC

57
00:03:28.208 --> 00:03:32.003
is the method originally proposed
in the first VQE publication,

58
00:03:32.295 --> 00:03:35.340
and it's commonly used in quantum
chemistry problems.

59
00:03:36.007 --> 00:03:38.676
Typically,
when we parameterized a quantum state,

60
00:03:39.010 --> 00:03:41.930
we work with exponentially
many parameters.

61
00:03:42.347 --> 00:03:45.058
However, to make preparation
circuits efficient,

62
00:03:45.308 --> 00:03:47.644
we need the polynomial number
of operations

63
00:03:47.644 --> 00:03:51.314
and therefore a polynomial number
of parameters.

64
00:03:51.814 --> 00:03:55.985
UCC is an example of a way of preparing
a trial state with such a circuit

65
00:03:56.319 --> 00:03:59.239
and it derives from a coupled cluster
method,

66
00:03:59.239 --> 00:04:01.866
which is the golden standard in quantum
chemistry.

67
00:04:02.575 --> 00:04:05.703
The most common choice is the unitary
coupled cluster

68
00:04:05.703 --> 00:04:10.500
singles and doubles
ansatz or UCCSD in short.

69
00:04:11.125 --> 00:04:16.630
Because UCCSD is motivated by specific
electronic configuration of a problem,

70
00:04:16.839 --> 00:04:21.928
we need to ensure we have a reference
state which properly reflects the system.

71
00:04:22.553 --> 00:04:24.596
This is the Hartree-Fock state.

72
00:04:24.597 --> 00:04:29.435
UCCSD ansatz usually gives
a good approximation of the ground state

73
00:04:29.435 --> 00:04:35.233
because it captures single and double
electron excitations in a given molecule.

74
00:04:35.233 --> 00:04:38.528
The number of parameters in UCCSD scales

75
00:04:38.528 --> 00:04:42.365
quadratically with the number of spin
orbitals.

76
00:04:42.365 --> 00:04:46.035
UCCSD can be very well
tailored to a problem,

77
00:04:46.286 --> 00:04:50.456
but unfortunately, quadratic scaling
still leads to very deep circuits

78
00:04:50.623 --> 00:04:53.209
which are difficult for current quantum
computers.

79
00:04:54.002 --> 00:04:58.089
This is why IBM researchers proposed
more heuristic approach,

80
00:04:58.339 --> 00:05:02.510
where one can tailor a variational form
to the underlying hardware

81
00:05:02.927 --> 00:05:06.180
which results in an efficiently
executable circuit.

82
00:05:06.848 --> 00:05:10.601
That is, trial states are parameterized
by quantum gates

83
00:05:10.810 --> 00:05:15.106
and are adapted
to the available physical device.

84
00:05:15.106 --> 00:05:18.735
This is a very heuristic approach
that is hardware friendly.

85
00:05:19.360 --> 00:05:22.989
Based on these examples, let's take a look
at the spectrum of possibilities

86
00:05:22.989 --> 00:05:26.075
that we have to express
our variational form.

87
00:05:26.868 --> 00:05:29.829
A lot of these
are already implemented in Qiskit

88
00:05:30.038 --> 00:05:32.623
so I encourage you to try out for yourself

89
00:05:32.790 --> 00:05:35.710
which one is the most suitable
for the problem you're trying to solve.

90
00:05:36.502 --> 00:05:40.214
If we look at the graph, on the one hand
we have the very heuristic

91
00:05:40.214 --> 00:05:41.466
variational forms.

92
00:05:41.466 --> 00:05:44.635
When the problem specificity is low, but

93
00:05:44.635 --> 00:05:47.513
they are designed to be implemented
on the real hardware.

94
00:05:48.306 --> 00:05:51.059
They are also highly expressive,
all in the sense

95
00:05:51.059 --> 00:05:54.103
that one can express
many quantum states with them.

96
00:05:54.979 --> 00:05:57.815
However,
a problem that may occur in the later

97
00:05:57.815 --> 00:06:00.818
stage of classical optimization
is encountering

98
00:06:00.818 --> 00:06:04.989
the so-called barren plateau,
which we will discuss in the next module.

99
00:06:05.490 --> 00:06:09.368
On the other hand,
we have a highly problem specific unitary

100
00:06:09.369 --> 00:06:14.248
coupled cluster, which works
excellent in classical chemistry but

101
00:06:14.248 --> 00:06:18.961
is difficult to implement on the quantum
hardware because of large circuit depths.

102
00:06:19.754 --> 00:06:23.132
Generally, calculations
can be more successful if you can,

103
00:06:23.466 --> 00:06:27.512
first of all choose a reference state
and initial set of parameters

104
00:06:27.720 --> 00:06:31.057
that create an ansatz state
close to the ground state.

105
00:06:31.349 --> 00:06:35.436
And second, avoid unnecessary parameters.

106
00:06:36.104 --> 00:06:39.857
These either introduce
greater circuit depth with no payoff

107
00:06:40.149 --> 00:06:42.944
or create a larger parameter space

108
00:06:43.152 --> 00:06:46.239
to search leading to plateaus
in the classical optimization.

109
00:06:47.532 --> 00:06:49.992
What parameters are necessary is a problem

110
00:06:49.992 --> 00:06:53.121
specific question
that requires careful thought.

111
00:06:53.955 --> 00:06:56.082
Let's talk about where our guest of honor,

112
00:06:56.499 --> 00:06:59.043
the Hamiltonian, is hiding in all of this.

113
00:06:59.544 --> 00:07:02.964
As we learned in the previous section,
the Hamiltonian after qubit

114
00:07:02.964 --> 00:07:07.677
mapping is represented as a sum of
weighted strings of Pauli operators.

115
00:07:08.386 --> 00:07:11.681
Eventually, however,
we want to evaluate the expectation

116
00:07:11.681 --> 00:07:16.561
value of our Hamiltonian on the ansatz
state produced by the variational form.

117
00:07:17.103 --> 00:07:20.022
Luckily, quantum
mechanics is nice and linear

118
00:07:20.189 --> 00:07:23.025
and this is what we'll use
to get the expectation value.

119
00:07:23.693 --> 00:07:24.986
This is how it works.

120
00:07:24.986 --> 00:07:28.114
We know the Hamiltonian is a weighted
sum of Paulis

121
00:07:28.573 --> 00:07:31.742
because of linearity
the expectation value of the sum

122
00:07:31.993 --> 00:07:36.372
is equal to the sum of the expectation
values of each Pauli string.

123
00:07:36.831 --> 00:07:41.252
Well, this is great because as you already
know, measuring in the Pauli basis

124
00:07:41.419 --> 00:07:45.673
is as simple as a rotation
of a standard measurement basis.

125
00:07:46.215 --> 00:07:50.595
Instead of measuring the expectation value
on this huge Hamiltonian represented

126
00:07:50.595 --> 00:07:55.183
as a sum, we first evaluate expectation
values of individual terms

127
00:07:55.391 --> 00:07:58.186
and sum at the end
with corresponding weights.

128
00:07:59.061 --> 00:08:01.355
This is why in many resources

129
00:08:01.522 --> 00:08:04.734
you will see only single qubit rotations
after the ansatz.

130
00:08:05.109 --> 00:08:09.614
This is what implements the Hamiltonian
in every execution of the circuit.

131
00:08:10.573 --> 00:08:11.741
In the next video,

132
00:08:11.741 --> 00:08:15.161
we'll explore what happens
during the classical optimization step.

133
00:08:15.703 --> 00:08:16.912
I'll see you there.
